so imagine you've some generated assertion classes which are deeply nested like discussed [here](https://github.com/joel-costigliola/assertj-assertions-generator/issues/67) so you have some assertions like...

``` java
assertThat(foo).bar().whatnot().cheese().isNotNull(); 
assertThat(foo).bar().whatnot().beer().isEqualTo("Stella");
assertThat(foo).bar().whatnot().wine().isEqualTo("Shiraz");
```

there's some duplication. Now our IDEs can refactor those expressions to variables...

``` java
WhatnotAssert whatnot = assertThat(foo).bar().whatnot();
whatnot.cheese().isNotNull(); 
whatnot.beer().isEqualTo("Stella");
whatnot.wine().isEqualTo("Shiraz");
```

but I wonder if Java 8 lambdas could be used to make an XPath like variable/predicate chain via a single new method on AbstractAssert?

``` java
assertThat(foo).bar().whatnot().with(whatnot -> {
  whatnot.cheese().isNotNull(); 
  whatnot.beer().isEqualTo("Stella");
  whatnot.wine().isEqualTo("Shiraz");
});
```

The nice thing is the type inference to avoid the noise of the actual types of the assert classes; so the code feels cleaner yet is nice and DRY.

Not 100% sure on the name of the function; used `with` could be `assert` or something? Basically it just invokes the lamda with the current assertion object really ;).

Thoughts? Happy to submit a PR you think its a good idea
